53  //========================================================================
54  /// \short A Generalised Element class.
55  ///
56  /// The main components of a GeneralisedElement are:
57  /// - pointers to its internal and external Data, which are stored together
58  /// in a single array so that we need only store one pointer.
59  /// The internal Data are placed at the beginning
60  /// of the array and the external Data are stored at the end.
61  /// - a pointer to a global Time
62  /// - a lookup table that establishes the relation between local
63  /// and global equation numbers.
64  ///
65  /// We also provide interfaces for functions that compute the
66  /// element's Jacobian matrix and/or the Vector of residuals.
67  /// In addition, an interface that returns a mass matrix --- the matrix
68  /// of terms that multiply any time derivatives in the problem --- is
69  /// also provided to permit explicit time-stepping and the solution
70  /// of the generalised eigenproblems.
71  //========================================================================
72  class GeneralisedElement
73  {
74  private:
75 
76  /// \short Storage for the global equation numbers represented by the
77  /// degrees of freedom in the element.
78  unsigned long *Eqn_number;
79 
80  /// \short Storage for array of pointers to degrees of freedom ordered
81  /// by local equation number. This information is not needed, except in
82  /// continuation, bifurcation tracking and periodic orbit calculations.
83  /// It is not set up unless the control flag
84  /// Problem::Store_local_dof_pts_in_elements = true
85  double **Dof_pt;
86 
87  /// \short Storage for pointers to internal and external data.
88  /// The data is of the same type and so can be addressed by
89  /// a single pointer. The idea is that the array is of
90  /// total size Ninternal_data + Nexternal_data.
91  /// The internal data are stored at the beginning of the array
92  /// and the external data are stored at the end of the array.
93  Data** Data_pt;
94 
95  /// \short Pointer to array storage for local equation numbers associated
96  /// with internal and external data. Again, we save storage by using
97  /// a single pointer to access this information. The first index of the
98  /// array is of dimension Nineternal_data + Nexternal_data and the second
99  /// index varies with the number of values stored at the data object.
100  /// In the most general case, however, the scheme is as memory efficient
101  /// as possible.
102  int** Data_local_eqn;
103 
104  /// Number of degrees of freedom
105  unsigned Ndof;
106 
107  /// Number of internal data
108  unsigned Ninternal_data;
109 
110  /// Number of external data
111  unsigned Nexternal_data;
112 
113  /// \short Storage for boolean flags of size Ninternal_data + Nexternal_data
114  /// that correspond to the data used in the element. The flags
115  /// indicate whether the particular
116  /// internal or external data should be included in the general
117  /// finite-difference loop in fill_in_jacobian_from_internal_by_fd() or
118  /// fill_in_jacobian_from_external_by_fd(). The default is that all
119  /// data WILL be included in the finite-difference loop, but in many
120  /// circumstances it is possible to treat certain (external) data
121  /// analytically. The use of an STL vector is optimal for memory
122  /// use because the booleans are represented as single-bits.
123  std::vector<bool> Data_fd;
124 
125  protected:
126 
127 #ifdef OOMPH_HAS_MPI
128 
129  /// \short Non-halo processor ID for Data; -1 if it's not a halo.
130  int Non_halo_proc_ID;
131 
132  /// Does this element need to be kept as a halo element during a distribute?
133  bool Must_be_kept_as_halo;
134 
135 #endif
136 
137  /// \short Add a (pointer to an) internal data object to the element and
138  /// return the index required to obtain it from the access
139  /// function \c internal_data_pt(). The boolean indicates whether
140  /// the datum should be included in the general finite-difference loop
141  /// when calculating the jacobian. The default value is true, i.e.
142  /// the data will be included in the finite differencing.
143  unsigned add_internal_data(Data* const &data_pt, const bool &fd=true);
144 
145 
146  /// \short Return the status of the boolean flag indicating whether
147  /// the internal data is included in the finite difference loop
148  inline bool internal_data_fd(const unsigned &i) const
149  {
150 #ifdef RANGE_CHECKING
151  if (i >= Ninternal_data)
152  {
153  std::ostringstream error_message;
154  error_message << "Range Error: Internal data " << i
155  << " is not in the range (0,"
156  << Ninternal_data-1 << ")";
157  throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
158  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
159  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
160  }
161 #endif
162  //Return the value
163  return Data_fd[i];
164  }
165 
166 
167  /// \short Set the boolean flag to exclude the internal datum from
168  /// the finite difference loop when computing the jacobian matrix
169  inline void exclude_internal_data_fd(const unsigned &i)
170  {
171 #ifdef RANGE_CHECKING
172  if (i >= Ninternal_data)
173  {
174  std::ostringstream error_message;
175  error_message << "Range Error: Internal data " << i
176  << " is not in the range (0,"
177  << Ninternal_data-1 << ")";
178  throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
179  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
180  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
181  }
182 #endif
183  //Set the value
184  Data_fd[i] = false;
185  }
186 
187  /// \short Set the boolean flag to include the internal datum in
188  /// the finite difference loop when computing the jacobian matrix
189  inline void include_internal_data_fd(const unsigned &i)
190  {
191 #ifdef RANGE_CHECKING
192  if (i >= Ninternal_data)
193  {
194  std::ostringstream error_message;
195  error_message << "Range Error: Internal data " << i
196  << " is not in the range (0,"
197  << Ninternal_data-1 << ")";
198  throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
199  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
200  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
201  }
202 #endif
203  //Set the value
204  Data_fd[i] = true;
205  }
206 
207  /// \short Clear the storage for the global equation numbers
208  /// and pointers to dofs (if stored)
209  void clear_global_eqn_numbers()
210  {delete[] Eqn_number; Eqn_number=0; delete[] Dof_pt; Dof_pt=0; Ndof=0;}
211 
212  /// \short Add the contents of the queue global_eqn_numbers
213  /// to the local storage for the local-to-global translation scheme.
214  /// It is essential that the entries in the queue are added IN ORDER
215  /// i.e. from the front.
216  void add_global_eqn_numbers(std::deque<unsigned long>
217  const &global_eqn_numbers,
218  std::deque<double*>
219  const &global_dof_pt);
220 
221  /// \short Empty dense matrix used as a dummy argument to combined
222  /// residual and jacobian functions in the case when only the residuals
223  /// are being assembled
224  static DenseMatrix<double> Dummy_matrix;
225 
226  /// \short Static storage for deque used to add_global_equation_numbers
227  /// when pointers to the dofs in each element are not required
228  static std::deque<double*> Dof_pt_deque;
229 
230  /// \short Assign the local equation numbers for the internal
231  /// and external Data
232  /// This must be called after the global equation numbers have all been
233  /// assigned. It is virtual so that it can be overloaded by
234  /// ElementWithExternalElements so that any external data from the
235  /// external elements in included in the numbering scheme.
236  /// If the boolean argument is true then pointers to the dofs will be
237  /// stored in Dof_pt
238  virtual void assign_internal_and_external_local_eqn_numbers(
239  const bool &store_local_dof_pt);
240 
241  /// \short Assign all the local equation numbering schemes that can
242  /// be applied generically for the element. In most cases, this is the
243  /// function that will be overloaded by inherited classes. It is required
244  /// to ensure that assign_additional_local_eqn_numbers() can always be
245  /// called after ALL other local equation numbering has been performed.
246  /// The default for the GeneralisedElement is simply to call internal
247  /// and external local equation numbering.
248  /// If the boolean argument is true then pointers to the dofs will be stored
249  /// in Dof_pt
250  virtual inline void assign_all_generic_local_eqn_numbers(
251  const bool &store_local_dof_pt)
252  {
253  this->assign_internal_and_external_local_eqn_numbers(store_local_dof_pt);
254  }
255 
256  /// \short Setup any additional look-up schemes for local equation numbers.
257  /// Examples of use include using local storage to refer to explicit
258  /// degrees of freedom. The additional memory cost of such storage may
259  /// or may not be offset by fast local access.
260  virtual void assign_additional_local_eqn_numbers() {}
261 
262  /// \short Return the local equation number corresponding to the j-th
263  /// value stored at the i-th internal data
264  inline int internal_local_eqn(const unsigned &i, const unsigned &j) const
265  {
266 #ifdef RANGE_CHECKING
267  if (i >= Ninternal_data)
268  {
269  std::ostringstream error_message;
270  error_message << "Range Error: Internal data " << i
271  << " is not in the range (0,"
272  << Ninternal_data-1 << ")";
273  throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
274  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
275  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
276  }
277  else
278  {
279  unsigned n_value = internal_data_pt(i)->nvalue();
280  if (j >= n_value)
281  {
282  std::ostringstream error_message;
283  error_message << "Range Error: value " << j << " at internal data "
284  << i
285  << " is not in the range (0,"
286  << n_value -1 << ")";
287  throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
288  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
289  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
290  }
291  }
292 #endif
293  //Check that the data has been allocated
294 #ifdef PARANOID
295  if (Data_local_eqn==0)
296  {
297  throw OomphLibError(
298  "Internal local equation numbers have not been allocated",
299  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
300  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
301  }
302 #endif
303  //Return the local equation number as stored in the Data_local_eqn array
304  return Data_local_eqn[i][j];
305  }
306 
307  /// \short Return the local equation number corresponding to the j-th
308  /// value stored at the i-th external data
309  inline int external_local_eqn(const unsigned &i, const unsigned &j)
310  {
311  //Check that the data has been allocated
312 #ifdef RANGE_CHECKING
313  if (i >= Nexternal_data)
314  {
315  std::ostringstream error_message;
316  error_message << "Range Error: External data " << i
317  << " is not in the range (0,"
318  << Nexternal_data-1 << ")";
319  throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
320  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
321  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
322  }
323  else
324  {
325  unsigned n_value = external_data_pt(i)->nvalue();
326  if (j >= n_value)
327  {
328  std::ostringstream error_message;
329  error_message << "Range Error: value " << j << " at internal data "
330  << i
331  << " is not in the range (0,"
332  << n_value -1 << ")";
333  throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
334  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
335  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
336  }
337  }
338 #endif
339 #ifdef PARANOID
340  if (Data_local_eqn==0)
341  {
342  throw OomphLibError(
343  "External local equation numbers have not been allocated",
344  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
345  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
346  }
347 #endif
348  //Return the local equation number stored as the j-th value of the
349  //i-th external data object.
350  return Data_local_eqn[Ninternal_data +i][j];
351  }
352 
353  /// \short Add the elemental contribution to the residuals vector. Note that
354  /// this function will NOT initialise the residuals vector. It must be
355  /// called after the residuals vector has been initialised to zero.
356  virtual void fill_in_contribution_to_residuals(Vector<double> &residuals)
357  {
358  std::string error_message =
359  "Empty fill_in_contribution_to_residuals() has been called.\n";
360  error_message +=
361  "This function is called from the default implementations of\n";
362  error_message +=
363  "get_residuals() and get_jacobian();\n";
364  error_message +=
365  "and must calculate the residuals vector without initialising any of ";
366  error_message += "its entries.\n\n";
367 
368  error_message +=
369  "If you do not wish to use these defaults, you must overload both\n";
370  error_message +=
371  "get_residuals() and get_jacobian(), which must initialise the entries\n";
372  error_message +=
373  "of the residuals vector and jacobian matrix to zero.\n";
374 
375  error_message +=
376  "N.B. the default get_jacobian() function employs finite differencing\n";
377 
378  throw OomphLibError(error_message,
379  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
380  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
381  }
382 
383  /// \short Calculate the contributions to the jacobian from the internal
384  /// degrees of freedom using finite differences.
385  /// This version of the function assumes that the residuals vector has
386  /// already been calculated. If the boolean argument is true, the finite
387  /// differencing will be performed for all internal data, irrespective of
388  /// the information in Data_fd. The default value (false)
389  /// uses the information in Data_fd to selectively difference only
390  /// certain data.
391  void fill_in_jacobian_from_internal_by_fd(Vector<double> &residuals,
392  DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian,
393  const bool &fd_all_data=false);
394 
395  /// \short Calculate the contributions to the jacobian from the internal
396  /// degrees of freedom using finite differences. This version computes
397  /// the residuals vector before calculating the jacobian terms.
398  /// If the boolean argument is true, the finite
399  /// differencing will be performed for all internal data, irrespective of
400  /// the information in Data_fd. The default value (false)
401  /// uses the information in Data_fd to selectively difference only
402  /// certain data.
403  void fill_in_jacobian_from_internal_by_fd(DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian,
404  const bool &fd_all_data=false)
405  {
406  //Allocate storage for the residuals
407  Vector<double> residuals(Ndof,0.0);
408  //Get the residuals for the entire element
409  get_residuals(residuals);
410  //Call the jacobian calculation
411  fill_in_jacobian_from_internal_by_fd(residuals,jacobian,fd_all_data);
412  }
413 
414 
415  /// \short Calculate the contributions to the jacobian from the external
416  /// degrees of freedom using finite differences.
417  /// This version of the function assumes that the residuals vector has
418  /// already been calculated.
419  /// If the boolean argument is true, the finite
420  /// differencing will be performed for all external data, irrespective of
421  /// the information in Data_fd. The default value (false)
422  /// uses the information in Data_fd to selectively difference only
423  /// certain data.
424  void fill_in_jacobian_from_external_by_fd(Vector<double> &residuals,
425  DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian,
426  const bool &fd_all_data=false);
427 
428 
429  /// \short Calculate the contributions to the jacobian from the external
430  /// degrees of freedom using finite differences. This version computes
431  /// the residuals vector before calculating the jacobian terms.
432  /// If the boolean argument is true, the finite
433  /// differencing will be performed for all internal data, irrespective of
434  /// the information in Data_fd. The default value (false)
435  /// uses the information in Data_fd to selectively difference only
436  /// certain data.
437  void fill_in_jacobian_from_external_by_fd(DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian,
438  const bool &fd_all_data=false)
439  {
440  //Allocate storage for a residuals vector
441  Vector<double> residuals(Ndof);
442  //Get the residuals for the entire element
443  get_residuals(residuals);
444  //Call the jacobian calculation
445  fill_in_jacobian_from_external_by_fd(residuals,jacobian,fd_all_data);
446  }

448  /// \short Function that is called before the finite differencing of
449  /// any internal data. This may be overloaded to update any dependent
450  /// data before finite differencing takes place.
451  virtual inline void update_before_internal_fd() { }
452 
453  /// \short Function that is call after the finite differencing of
454  /// the internal data. This may be overloaded to reset any dependent
455  /// variables that may have changed during the finite differencing.
456  virtual inline void reset_after_internal_fd() { }
457 
458  /// \short Function called within the finite difference loop for
459  /// internal data after a change in any values in the i-th
460  /// internal data object.
461  virtual inline void update_in_internal_fd(const unsigned &i) { }
462 
463  /// \short Function called within the finite difference loop for
464  /// internal data after the values in the i-th external data object
465  /// are reset. The default behaviour is to call the update function.
466  virtual inline void reset_in_internal_fd(const unsigned &i)
467  {update_in_internal_fd(i);}

475  /// \short Function that is call after the finite differencing of

484 
485  /// \short Function called within the finite difference loop for
486  /// external data after the values in the i-th external data object
487  /// are reset. The default behaviour is to call the update function.

491  /// \short Add the elemental contribution to the jacobian matrix.
492  /// and the residuals vector. Note that
493  /// this function will NOT initialise the residuals vector or the jacobian
494  /// matrix. It must be called after the residuals vector and
495  /// jacobian matrix have been initialised to zero. The default
496  /// is to use finite differences to calculate the jacobian
497  virtual void fill_in_contribution_to_jacobian(Vector<double> &residuals,
498  DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian)
499  {
500  //Add the contribution to the residuals
501  fill_in_contribution_to_residuals(residuals);
502  //Allocate storage for the full residuals (residuals of entire element)
503  Vector<double> full_residuals(Ndof);
504  //Get the residuals for the entire element
505  get_residuals(full_residuals);
506  //Calculate the contributions from the internal dofs
507  //(finite-difference the lot by default)
508  fill_in_jacobian_from_internal_by_fd(full_residuals,jacobian,true);
509  //Calculate the contributions from the external dofs
510  //(finite-difference the lot by default)
511  fill_in_jacobian_from_external_by_fd(full_residuals,jacobian,true);
512  }
513 
514  /// \short Add the elemental contribution to the mass matrix matrix.
515  /// and the residuals vector. Note that
516  /// this function should NOT initialise the residuals vector or the mass
517  /// matrix. It must be called after the residuals vector and
518  /// jacobian matrix have been initialised to zero. The default
519  /// is deliberately broken
520  virtual void fill_in_contribution_to_mass_matrix(
521  Vector<double> &residuals, DenseMatrix<double> &mass_matrix);
522 
523  /// \short Add the elemental contribution to the jacobian matrix,
524  /// mass matrix and the residuals vector. Note that
525  /// this function should NOT initialise any entries.
526  /// It must be called after the residuals vector and
527  /// matrices have been initialised to zero.
528  virtual void fill_in_contribution_to_jacobian_and_mass_matrix(
529  Vector<double> &residuals,
530  DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian, DenseMatrix<double> &mass_matrix);
531 
532  /// \short Add the elemental contribution to the derivatives of
533  /// the residuals with respect to a parameter. This function should
534  /// NOT initialise any entries and must be called after the entries
535  /// have been initialised to zero
536  /// The default implementation is to use finite differences to calculate
537  /// the derivatives.
538  virtual void fill_in_contribution_to_dresiduals_dparameter(
539  double* const &parameter_pt,
540  Vector<double> &dres_dparam);
541 
542 
543  /// \short Add the elemental contribution to the derivatives of
544  /// the elemental Jacobian matrix
545  /// and residuals with respect to a parameter. This function should
546  /// NOT initialise any entries and must be called after the entries
547  /// have been initialised to zero
548  /// The default implementation is to use finite differences to calculate
549  /// the derivatives.
550  virtual void fill_in_contribution_to_djacobian_dparameter(
551  double* const &parameter_pt,
552  Vector<double> &dres_dparam,
553  DenseMatrix<double> &djac_dparam);
554 
555  /// \short Add the elemental contribution to the derivative of the

559  /// this function should NOT initialise any entries.
560  /// It must be called after the residuals vector and

562  virtual void fill_in_contribution_to_djacobian_and_dmass_matrix_dparameter(
563  double* const &parameter_pt,

569  /// \short Fill in contribution to the product of the Hessian
570  /// (derivative of Jacobian with
571  /// respect to all variables) an eigenvector, Y, and
572  /// other specified vectors, C
573  /// (d(J_{ij})/d u_{k}) Y_{j} C_{k}
574  virtual void fill_in_contribution_to_hessian_vector_products(
575  Vector<double> const &Y,

577  DenseMatrix<double> &product);

579  /// \short Fill in the contribution to the inner products between given
580  /// pairs of history values
581  virtual void fill_in_contribution_to_inner_products(

592  public:
593 
594  /// \short Constructor: Initialise all pointers and all values to zero
595  GeneralisedElement() :
596  Eqn_number(0), Dof_pt(0), Data_pt(0),
597  Data_local_eqn(0), Ndof(0), Ninternal_data(0), Nexternal_data(0)
598 #ifdef OOMPH_HAS_MPI
599  , Non_halo_proc_ID(-1) , Must_be_kept_as_halo(false)
600 #endif
601  {}

618  /// Return a pointer to i-th internal data object.

620  {

623  {
624  std::ostringstream error_message;
625  error_message << "Range Error: Internal data " << i
626  << " is not in the range (0,"
627  << Ninternal_data - 1 << ")";
628  throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
629  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
630  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
631 
632  }
633 #endif
634  return Data_pt[i];
635  }

703  /// \short Return the global equation number corresponding to the
704  /// ieqn_local-th local equation number
705  unsigned long eqn_number(const unsigned &ieqn_local) const
706  {
707 #ifdef RANGE_CHECKING
708  if (ieqn_local >= Ndof)
709  {
710  std::ostringstream error_message;
711  error_message << "Range Error: Equation number " << ieqn_local
712  << " is not in the range (0,"
713  << Ndof - 1 << ")";
714  throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
715  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
716  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
717  }
718 #endif
719  return Eqn_number[ieqn_local];
720  }

723  ///\short Return the local equation number corresponding to the ieqn_global-th
724  ///global equation number. Returns minus one (-1) if there is no
725  ///local degree of freedom corresponding to the chosen global equation
726  ///number
727  int local_eqn_number(const unsigned long &ieqn_global) const
728  {
729  //Cache the number of degrees of freedom in the element
730  const unsigned n_dof = this->Ndof;
731  //Loop over the local equation numbers
732  for (unsigned n=0; n<n_dof; n++)
733  {
734  //If the global equation numbers match return
735  if (ieqn_global==Eqn_number[n]) {return n;}
736  }
737 
738  //If we've got all the way to the end the number has not been found
739  //return minus one.
740  return -1;
741  }

832  ///\short Return the vector of dof values at time level t
833  void dof_vector(const unsigned &t, Vector<double> &dof)
834  {
835  //Check that the internal storage has been set up
836 #ifdef PARANOID
837  if (Dof_pt==0)
838  {
839  std::stringstream error_stream;
840  error_stream << "Internal dof array not set up in element.\n"
841  << "In order to set it up you must call\n"
842  << " Problem::enable_store_local_dof_in_elements()\n"
843  << "before the call to Problem::assign_eqn_numbers()\n";
844  throw OomphLibError(error_stream.str(),
845  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
846  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
847  }
848 #endif
849  //Resize the vector
850  dof.resize(this->Ndof);
851  //Loop over the vector and fill in the desired values
852  for (unsigned i=0; i<this->Ndof; ++i)
853  {
854  dof[i] = Dof_pt[i][t];
855  }
856  }
857 
858  ///\short Return the vector of pointers to dof values
859  void dof_pt_vector(Vector<double*> &dof_pt)
860  {
861  //Check that the internal storage has been set up
862 #ifdef PARANOID
863  if (Dof_pt==0)
864  {
865  std::stringstream error_stream;
866  error_stream << "Internal dof array not set up in element.\n"
867  << "In order to set it up you must call\n"
868  << " Problem::enable_store_local_dof_in_elements()\n"
869  << "before the call to Problem::assign_eqn_numbers()\n";
870  throw OomphLibError(error_stream.str(),
871  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
872  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
873  }
874 #endif
875  //Resize the vector
876  dof_pt.resize(this->Ndof);
877  //Loop over the vector and fill in the desired values
878  for (unsigned i=0; i<this->Ndof; ++i)
879  {
880  dof_pt[i] = Dof_pt[i];
881  }
882  }

959  /// \short Complete the setup of any additional dependencies
960  /// that the element may have. Empty virtual function that may be
961  /// overloaded for specific derived elements. Used, e.g., for elements
962  /// with algebraic node update functions to determine the "geometric
963  /// Data", i.e. the Data that affects the element's shape.
964  /// This function is called (for all elements) at the very beginning of the
965  /// equation numbering procedure to ensure that all dependencies
966  /// are accounted for.
967  virtual void complete_setup_of_dependencies() {}

969  /// \short Calculate the vector of residuals of the equations in the element.
970  /// By default initialise the vector to zero and then call the
971  /// fill_in_contribution_to_residuals() function. Note that this entire
972  /// function can be overloaded if desired.
973  virtual void get_residuals(Vector<double> &residuals)
974  {
975  //Zero the residuals vector
976  residuals.initialise(0.0);
977  //Add the elemental contribution to the residuals vector
978  fill_in_contribution_to_residuals(residuals);
979  }
980 
981  /// \short Calculate the elemental Jacobian matrix "d equation / d variable".
982  virtual void get_jacobian(Vector<double> &residuals,
983  DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian)
984  {
985  //Zero the residuals vector
986  residuals.initialise(0.0);
987  //Zero the jacobian matrix
988  jacobian.initialise(0.0);
989  //Add the elemental contribution to the residuals vector
990  fill_in_contribution_to_jacobian(residuals,jacobian);
991  }
992 
993  /// \short Calculate the residuals and the elemental "mass" matrix, the
994  /// matrix that multiplies the time derivative terms in a problem.
995  virtual void get_mass_matrix(Vector<double> &residuals,
996  DenseMatrix<double> &mass_matrix)
997  {
998  //Zero the residuals vector
999  residuals.initialise(0.0);
1000  //Zero the mass matrix
1001  mass_matrix.initialise(0.0);
1002  //Add the elemental contribution to the vector and matrix
1003  fill_in_contribution_to_mass_matrix(residuals,mass_matrix);
1004  }
1005 
1006  /// \short Calculate the residuals and jacobian and elemental "mass" matrix,
1007  /// the matrix that multiplies the time derivative terms.
1008  virtual void get_jacobian_and_mass_matrix(Vector<double> &residuals,
1009  DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian,
1010  DenseMatrix<double> &mass_matrix)
1011  {
1012  //Zero the residuals vector
1013  residuals.initialise(0.0);
1014  //Zero the jacobian matrix
1015  jacobian.initialise(0.0);
1016  //Zero the mass matrix
1017  mass_matrix.initialise(0.0);
1018  //Add the elemental contribution to the vector and matrix
1019  fill_in_contribution_to_jacobian_and_mass_matrix(residuals,jacobian,
1020  mass_matrix);
1021  }

1036  /// \short Calculate the derivatives of the elemental Jacobian matrix
1037  /// and residuals with respect to a parameter
1038  virtual void get_djacobian_dparameter(double* const &parameter_pt,
1039  Vector<double> &dres_dparam,
1040  DenseMatrix<double> &djac_dparam)
1041  {
1042  //Zero the residuals vector
1043  dres_dparam.initialise(0.0);
1044  //Zero the jacobian matrix
1045  djac_dparam.initialise(0.0);

1051  /// \short Calculate the derivatives of the elemental Jacobian matrix
1052  /// mass matrix and residuals with respect to a parameter
1053  virtual void get_djacobian_and_dmass_matrix_dparameter(
1054  double* const &parameter_pt,
1055  Vector<double> &dres_dparam,
1056  DenseMatrix<double> &djac_dparam,
1057  DenseMatrix<double> &dmass_matrix_dparam)
1058  {
1059  //Zero the residuals derivative vector
1060  dres_dparam.initialise(0.0);
1061  //Zero the jacobian derivative matrix
1062  djac_dparam.initialise(0.0);
1063  //Zero the mass matrix derivative
1064  dmass_matrix_dparam.initialise(0.0);
1065  //Add the elemental contribution to the residuals vector and matrices
1066  this->fill_in_contribution_to_djacobian_and_dmass_matrix_dparameter(
1067  parameter_pt,dres_dparam,djac_dparam,dmass_matrix_dparam);
1068  }

1071  /// \short Calculate the product of the Hessian (derivative of Jacobian with
1072  /// respect to all variables) an eigenvector, Y, and
1073  /// other specified vectors, C
1074  /// (d(J_{ij})/d u_{k}) Y_{j} C_{k}
1075  virtual void get_hessian_vector_products(Vector<double> const &Y,
1076  DenseMatrix<double> const &C,
1077  DenseMatrix<double> &product)
1078  {
1079  //Initialise the product to zero
1080  product.initialise(0.0);
1081  ///Add the elemental contribution to the product
1082  this->fill_in_contribution_to_hessian_vector_products(Y,C,product);
1083  }

1087  virtual void get_inner_products(Vector<std::pair<unsigned,unsigned> >
1088  const &history_index,
1089  Vector<double> &inner_product)
1090  {
1091  inner_product.initialise(0.0);

1093  inner_product);

1096  /// \short Compute the vectors that when taken as a dot product with
1097  /// other history values give the inner product over the element.
1098  virtual void get_inner_product_vectors(Vector<unsigned> const &history_index,
1099  Vector<Vector<double> > &inner_product_vector)
1100  {
1101  const unsigned n_inner_product = inner_product_vector.size();
1102  for (unsigned i=0; i<n_inner_product; ++i)
1103  {inner_product_vector[i].initialise(0.0);}
1104  this->fill_in_contribution_to_inner_product_vectors(history_index,
1105  inner_product_vector);
1106  }

1271  //========================================================================
1272  /// \short A general Finite Element class.
1273  ///
1274  /// The main components of a FiniteElement are:
1275  /// - pointers to its Nodes
1276  /// - pointers to its internal Data (inherited from GeneralisedElement)
1277  /// - pointers to its external Data (inherited from GeneralisedElement)
1278  /// - a pointer to a spatial integration scheme
1279  /// - a pointer to the global Time object (inherited from GeneralisedElement)
1280  /// - a lookup table which establishes the relation between local
1281  /// and global equation numbers (inherited from GeneralisedElement)
1282  ///
1283  /// We also provide interfaces for functions that compute the
1284  /// element's Jacobian matrix and/or the Vector of residuals
1285  /// (inherited from GeneralisedElement) plus various output routines.
1286  //========================================================================
1287  class FiniteElement : public virtual GeneralisedElement, public GeomObject
1288  {
1289  private:
1290 
1291  /// Pointer to the spatial integration scheme
1292  Integral* Integral_pt;
1293 
1294  /// Storage for pointers to the nodes in the element
1295  Node** Node_pt;
1296 
1297  /// \short Storage for the local equation numbers associated with
1298  /// the values stored at the nodes
1299  int** Nodal_local_eqn;
1300 
1301  /// Number of nodes in the element
1302  unsigned Nnode;
1303 
1304  /// \short The spatial dimension of the element, i.e. the number
1305  /// of local coordinates used to parametrize it.
1306  unsigned Elemental_dimension;
1307 
1308  /// \short The spatial dimension of the nodes in the element.
1309  /// We assume that nodes have the same spatial dimension, because
1310  /// we cannot think of any "real" problems for which that would not
1311  /// be the case.
1312  unsigned Nodal_dimension;
1313 
1314  /// \short The number of coordinate types required to interpolate
1315  /// the element's geometry between the nodes. For Lagrange elements
1316  /// it is 1 (the default). It must be over-ridden by using
1317  /// the set_nposition_type() function in the constructors of elements
1318  /// that use generalised coordinate, e.g. for 1D Hermite elements
1319  /// Nnodal_position_types =2.
1320  unsigned Nnodal_position_type;
1321 
1322  protected:
1323 
1324  /// \short Assemble the jacobian matrix for the mapping from local
1325  /// to Eulerian coordinates, given the derivatives of the shape function
1326  /// w.r.t the local coordinates.
1327  virtual void assemble_local_to_eulerian_jacobian(
1328  const DShape &dpsids, DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian) const;
1329 
1330  /// \short Assemble the the "jacobian" matrix of second derivatives of the
1331  /// mapping from local to Eulerian coordinates, given
1332  /// the second derivatives of the shape functions w.r.t. local coordinates.
1333  virtual void assemble_local_to_eulerian_jacobian2(
1334  const DShape &d2psids, DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian2) const;
1335 
1336  /// \short Assemble the covariant Eulerian base vectors, assuming that
1337  /// the derivatives of the shape functions with respect to the local
1338  /// coordinates have already been constructed.
1339  virtual void assemble_eulerian_base_vectors(
1340  const DShape &dpsids, DenseMatrix<double> &interpolated_G) const;
1341 
1342  /// \short Default return value for required_nvalue(n) which gives the number
1343  /// of "data" values required by the element at node n; for example, solving
1344  /// a Poisson equation would required only one "data" value at each node. The
1345  /// defaults is set to zero, because a general element is problem-less.
1346  static const unsigned Default_Initial_Nvalue;
1347 
1348  /// \short Default value for the tolerance to be used when locating nodes
1349  /// via local coordinates
1350  static const double Node_location_tolerance;
1351 
1352  public:
1353 
1354  /// \short Set the dimension of the element and initially set
1355  /// the dimension of the nodes to be the same as the dimension of the
1356  /// element.
1357  void set_dimension(const unsigned &dim)
1358  {Elemental_dimension = dim; Nodal_dimension = dim;}
1359 
1360  /// \short Set the dimension of the nodes in the element. This will
1361  /// typically only be required when constructing FaceElements or
1362  /// in beam and shell type elements where a lower dimensional surface
1363  /// is embedded in a higher dimensional space.
1364  void set_nodal_dimension(const unsigned &nodal_dim)
1365  {Nodal_dimension = nodal_dim;}
1366 
1367  /// \short Set the number of types required to interpolate the coordinate
1368  void set_nnodal_position_type(const unsigned &nposition_type)
1369  {Nnodal_position_type = nposition_type;}
1370 
1371 
1372  /// \short Set the number of nodes in the element to n, by resizing
1373  /// the storage for pointers to the Node objects.
1374  void set_n_node(const unsigned &n)
1375  {
1376  //This should only be done once, in a Node constructor
1377  //#ifdef PARANOID
1378  //if(Node_pt)
1379  // {
1380  // OomphLibWarning(
1381  // "You are resetting the number of nodes in an element -- Be careful",
1382  // "FiniteElement::set_n_node()",
1383  // OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
1384  // }
1385  //#endif
1386  //Delete any previous storage to avoid memory leaks
1387  //This will only happen in very special cases
1388  delete[] Node_pt;
1389  //Set the number of nodes
1390  Nnode = n;
1391  //Allocate the storage
1392  Node_pt = new Node*[n];
1393  //Initialise all the pointers to NULL
1394  for (unsigned i=0; i<n; i++) {Node_pt[i] = 0;}
1395  }
1396 
1397  /// \short Return the local equation number corresponding to the i-th
1398  /// value at the n-th local node.
1399  inline int nodal_local_eqn(const unsigned &n, const unsigned &i) const
1400  {
1401 #ifdef RANGE_CHECKING
1402  if (n >= Nnode)
1403  {
1404  std::ostringstream error_message;
1405  error_message << "Range Error: Node number " << n
1406  << " is not in the range (0,"
1407  << Nnode-1 << ")";
1408  throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
1409  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
1410  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
1411  }
1412  else
1413  {
1414  unsigned n_value = node_pt(n)->nvalue();
1415  if (i >= n_value)
1416  {
1417  std::ostringstream error_message;
1418  error_message << "Range Error: value " << i << " at node " << n
1419  << " is not in the range (0,"
1420  << n_value -1 << ")";
1421  throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
1422  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
1423  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
1424  }
1425  }
1426 #endif
1427 #ifdef PARANOID
1428  //Check that the equations have been allocated
1429  if (Nodal_local_eqn==0)
1430  {
1431  throw OomphLibError(
1432  "Nodal local equation numbers have not been allocated",
1433  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
1434  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
1435  }
1436 #endif
1437  return Nodal_local_eqn[n][i];
1438  }

1442  /// \short Compute the geometric shape functions (psi) at integration point
1443  /// ipt. Return the determinant of the jacobian of the mapping (detJ).
1444  /// Additionally calculate the derivatives of "detJ" w.r.t. the
1445  /// nodal coordinates.
1446  double dJ_eulerian_at_knot(const unsigned &ipt,
1447  Shape &psi,
1448  DenseMatrix<double> &djacobian_dX) const;
1449  protected:
1450 
1451  /// \short Static array that holds the number of second derivatives
1452  /// as a function of the dimension of the element
1453  static const unsigned N2deriv[];
1454 
1455  /// \short Take the matrix passed as jacobian and return its inverse in
1456  /// inverse_jacobian. This function is templated by the dimension of the
1457  /// element because matrix inversion cannot be written efficiently in a
1458  /// generic manner.
1459  template<unsigned DIM>
1460  double invert_jacobian(const DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian,
1461  DenseMatrix<double> &inverse_jacobian) const;
1462 
1463 
1464  /// \short A template-free interface that takes the matrix passed as jacobian
1465  /// and return its inverse in inverse_jacobian. By default the function will
1466  /// use the dimension of the element to call the correct invert_jacobian(..)
1467  /// function. This should be overloaded for efficiency (removal of a switch
1468  /// statement) in specific elements.
1469  virtual double invert_jacobian_mapping(const DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian,
1470  DenseMatrix<double> &inverse_jacobian)
1471  const;
1472 
1473 
1474  /// \short Calculate the mapping from local to Eulerian coordinates,
1475  /// given the derivatives of the shape functions w.r.t. local coordinates.
1476  /// Returns the determinant of the jacobian, the jacobian and inverse jacobian
1477  virtual double local_to_eulerian_mapping(const DShape &dpsids,
1478  DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian,
1479  DenseMatrix<double> &inverse_jacobian) const
1480  {
1481  //Assemble the jacobian
1482  assemble_local_to_eulerian_jacobian(dpsids,jacobian);
1483  //Invert the jacobian (use the template-free interface)
1484  return invert_jacobian_mapping(jacobian,inverse_jacobian);
1485  }
1486 
1487 
1488  /// \short Calculate the mapping from local to Eulerian coordinates,
1489  /// given the derivatives of the shape functions w.r.t. local coordinates,
1490  /// Return only the determinant of the jacobian and the inverse of the
1491  /// mapping (ds/dx).
1492  double local_to_eulerian_mapping(const DShape &dpsids,
1493  DenseMatrix<double> &inverse_jacobian) const
1494  {
1495  //Find the dimension of the element
1496  const unsigned el_dim = dim();
1497  //Assign memory for the jacobian
1498  DenseMatrix<double> jacobian(el_dim);
1499  //Calculate the jacobian and inverse
1500  return local_to_eulerian_mapping(dpsids,jacobian,inverse_jacobian);
1501  }
1502 
1503  /// \short Calculate the mapping from local to Eulerian coordinates given
1504  /// the derivatives of the shape functions w.r.t the local coordinates.
1505  /// assuming that the coordinates are aligned in the direction of the local
1506  /// coordinates, i.e. there are no cross terms and the jacobian is diagonal.
1507  /// This function returns the determinant of the jacobian, the jacobian
1508  /// and the inverse jacobian.
1509  virtual double local_to_eulerian_mapping_diagonal(
1510  const DShape &dpsids,DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian,
1511  DenseMatrix<double> &inverse_jacobian) const;
1512 
1513  /// \short A template-free interface that calculates the derivative of the
1514  /// jacobian of a mapping with respect to the nodal coordinates X_ij.
1515  /// To do this it requires the jacobian matrix and the derivatives of the
1516  /// shape functions w.r.t. the local coordinates. By default the function
1517  /// will use the dimension of the element to call the correct
1518  /// dJ_eulerian_dnodal_coordinates_templated_helper(..) function. This
1519  /// should be overloaded for efficiency (removal of a switch statement)
1520  /// in specific elements.
1521  virtual void dJ_eulerian_dnodal_coordinates(
1522  const DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian,const DShape &dpsids,
1523  DenseMatrix<double> &djacobian_dX) const;
1524 
1525  /// \short Calculate the derivative of the jacobian of a mapping with
1526  /// respect to the nodal coordinates X_ij using the jacobian matrix
1527  /// and the derivatives of the shape functions w.r.t. the local
1528  /// coordinates. This function is templated by the dimension of the
1529  /// element.
1530  template<unsigned DIM>
1531  void dJ_eulerian_dnodal_coordinates_templated_helper(
1532  const DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian,const DShape &dpsids,
1533  DenseMatrix<double> &djacobian_dX) const;
1534 
1535  /// \short A template-free interface that calculates the derivative w.r.t.
1536  /// the nodal coordinates \f$ X_{pq} \f$ of the derivative of the shape
1537  /// functions \f$ \psi_j \f$ w.r.t. the global eulerian coordinates
1538  /// \f$ x_i \f$. I.e. this function calculates
1539  /// \f[
1540  /// \frac{\partial}{\partial X_{pq}}
1541  /// \left( \frac{\partial \psi_j}{\partial x_i} \right).
1542  /// \f]
1543  /// To do this it requires the determinant of the jacobian mapping, its
1544  /// derivative w.r.t. the nodal coordinates \f$ X_{pq} \f$, the inverse
1545  /// jacobian and the derivatives of the shape functions w.r.t. the local
1546  /// coordinates. The result is returned as a tensor of rank four.
1547  /// Numbering:
1548  /// d_dpsidx_dX(p,q,j,i) = \f$ \frac{\partial}{\partial X_{pq}}
1549  /// \left( \frac{\partial \psi_j}{\partial x_i} \right) \f$
1550  /// By default the function will use the dimension of the element to call
1551  /// the correct d_dshape_eulerian_dnodal_coordinates_templated_helper(..)
1552  /// function. This should be overloaded for efficiency (removal of a
1553  /// switch statement) in specific elements.
1554  virtual void d_dshape_eulerian_dnodal_coordinates(
1555  const double &det_jacobian,
1556  const DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian,
1557  const DenseMatrix<double> &djacobian_dX,
1558  const DenseMatrix<double> &inverse_jacobian,
1559  const DShape &dpsids,
1560  RankFourTensor<double> &d_dpsidx_dX) const;
1561 
1562  /// \short Calculate the derivative w.r.t. the nodal coordinates
1563  /// \f$ X_{pq} \f$ of the derivative of the shape functions w.r.t. the
1564  /// global eulerian coordinates \f$ x_i \f$, using the determinant of
1565  /// the jacobian mapping, its derivative w.r.t. the nodal coordinates
1566  /// \f$ X_{pq} \f$, the inverse jacobian and the derivatives of the
1567  /// shape functions w.r.t. the local coordinates. The result is returned
1568  /// as a tensor of rank four.
1569  /// Numbering:
1570  /// d_dpsidx_dX(p,q,j,i) = \f$ \frac{\partial}{\partial X_{pq}}
1571  /// \left( \frac{\partial \psi_j}{\partial x_i} \right) \f$
1572  /// This function is templated by the dimension of the element.
1573  template<unsigned DIM>
1574  void d_dshape_eulerian_dnodal_coordinates_templated_helper(
1575  const double &det_jacobian,
1576  const DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian,
1577  const DenseMatrix<double> &djacobian_dX,
1578  const DenseMatrix<double> &inverse_jacobian,
1579  const DShape &dpsids,
1580  RankFourTensor<double> &d_dpsidx_dX) const;
1581 
1582  /// \short Convert derivative w.r.t.local coordinates to derivatives
1583  /// w.r.t the coordinates used to assemble the inverse_jacobian passed
1584  /// in the mapping. On entry, dbasis must contain the basis function
1585  /// derivatives w.r.t. the local coordinates; it will contain the
1586  /// derivatives w.r.t. the new coordinates on exit.
1587  /// This is virtual so that it may be overloaded if desired
1588  /// for efficiency reasons.
1589  virtual void transform_derivatives(const DenseMatrix<double>
1590  &inverse_jacobian, DShape &dbasis) const;
1591 
1592  /// \short Convert derivative w.r.t local coordinates to derivatives
1593  /// w.r.t the coordinates used to assemble the inverse jacobian passed
1594  /// in the mapping, assuming that the coordinates are aligned in the
1595  /// direction of the local coordinates. On entry dbasis must contain
1596  /// the derivatives of the basis functions w.r.t. the local coordinates;
1597  /// it will contain the derivatives w.r.t. the new coordinates.
1598  /// are converted into the new using the mapping inverse_jacobian.
1599  void transform_derivatives_diagonal(const DenseMatrix<double>
1600  &inverse_jacobian, DShape &dbasis) const;
1601 
1602  /// \short Convert derivatives and second derivatives w.r.t. local coordiantes
1603  /// to derivatives and second derivatives w.r.t. the coordinates used to
1604  /// assemble the jacobian, inverse jacobian and jacobian2 passed to the
1605  /// function. By default this function will call
1606  /// transform_second_derivatives_template<>(...) using the dimension of
1607  /// the element as the template parameter. It is virtual so that it can
1608  /// be overloaded by a specific element to save using a switch statement.
1609  /// Optionally, the element writer may wish to use the
1610  /// transform_second_derivatives_diagonal<>(...) function
1611  /// On entry dbasis and d2basis must contain the derivatives w.r.t. the
1612  /// local coordinates; on exit they will be the derivatives w.r.t. the
1613  /// transformed coordinates.
1614  virtual void transform_second_derivatives(const DenseMatrix<double>
1615  &jacobian,
1616  const DenseMatrix<double>
1617  &inverse_jacobian,
1618  const DenseMatrix<double>
1619  &jacobian2,
1620  DShape &dbasis,
1621  DShape &d2basis) const;
1622 
1623  /// \short Convert derivatives and second derivatives w.r.t. local coordinates
1624  /// to derivatives and second derivatives w.r.t. the coordinates used to
1625  /// asssmble the jacobian, inverse jacobian and jacobian2 passed in the
1626  /// mapping. This is templated by dimension because the method of calculation
1627  /// varies significantly with the dimension.
1628  /// On entry dbasis and d2basis must contain the derivatives w.r.t. the
1629  /// local coordinates; on exit they will be the derivatives w.r.t. the
1630  /// transformed coordinates.
1631  template<unsigned DIM>
1632  void transform_second_derivatives_template(const DenseMatrix<double>
1633  &jacobian,
1634  const DenseMatrix<double>
1635  &inverse_jacobian,
1636  const DenseMatrix<double>
1637  &jacobian2,
1638  DShape &dbasis,
1639  DShape &d2basis) const;
1640 
1641  /// \short Convert derivatives and second derivatives w.r.t. local coordinates
1642  /// to derivatives and second derivatives w.r.t. the coordinates used to
1643  /// asssmble the jacobian, inverse jacobian and jacobian2 passed in the
1644  /// mapping. This version of the function assumes that the local coordinates
1645  /// are aligned with the global coordinates, i.e. the jacobians are diagonal
1646  /// On entry dbasis and d2basis must contain the derivatives w.r.t. the
1647  /// local coordinates; on exit they will be the derivatives w.r.t. the
1648  /// transformed coordinates.
1649  template<unsigned DIM>
1650  void transform_second_derivatives_diagonal(const DenseMatrix<double>
1651  &jacobian,
1652  const DenseMatrix<double>
1653  &inverse_jacobian,
1654  const DenseMatrix<double>
1655  &jacobian2,
1656  DShape &dbasis,
1657  DShape &d2basis) const;
1658 
1659  /// Pointer to the element's macro element (NULL by default)
1660  MacroElement* Macro_elem_pt;
1661 
1662  /// \short Calculate the contributions to the jacobian from the nodal
1663  /// degrees of freedom using finite differences.
1664  /// This version of the function assumes that the residuals vector has
1665  /// already been calculated
1666  virtual void fill_in_jacobian_from_nodal_by_fd(Vector<double> &residuals,
1667  DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian);
1668 
1669  /// \short Calculate the contributions to the jacobian from the nodal
1670  /// degrees of freedom using finite differences. This version computes
1671  /// the residuals vector before calculating the jacobian terms.
1672  void fill_in_jacobian_from_nodal_by_fd(DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian)
1673  {
1674  //Allocate storage for a residuals vector and initialise to zero
1675  unsigned n_dof = ndof();
1676  Vector<double> residuals(n_dof,0.0);
1677  //Get the residuals for the entire element
1678  get_residuals(residuals);
1679  //Call the jacobian calculation
1680  fill_in_jacobian_from_nodal_by_fd(residuals,jacobian);
1681  }
1682 
1683  /// \short Function that is called before the finite differencing of
1684  /// any nodal data. This may be overloaded to update any dependent
1685  /// data before finite differencing takes place.
1686  virtual inline void update_before_nodal_fd() { }
1687 
1688  /// \short Function that is call after the finite differencing of
1689  /// the nodal data. This may be overloaded to reset any dependent
1690  /// variables that may have changed during the finite differencing.
1691  virtual inline void reset_after_nodal_fd() { }
1692 
1693  /// \short Function called within the finite difference loop for
1694  /// nodal data after a change in the i-th nodal value.
1695  virtual inline void update_in_nodal_fd(const unsigned &i) { }
1696 
1697  /// \short Function called within the finite difference loop for
1698  /// nodal data after the i-th nodal values is reset.
1699  /// The default behaviour is to call the update function.
1700  virtual inline void reset_in_nodal_fd(const unsigned &i)
1701  {update_in_nodal_fd(i);}
1702 
1703 
1704  /// \short Add the elemental contribution to the jacobian matrix.
1705  /// and the residuals vector. Note that
1706  /// this function will NOT initialise the residuals vector or the jacobian
1707  /// matrix. It must be called after the residuals vector and
1708  /// jacobian matrix have been initialised to zero. The default
1709  /// is to use finite differences to calculate the jacobian
1710  void fill_in_contribution_to_jacobian(Vector<double> &residuals,
1711  DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian)
1712  {
1713  //Add the contribution to the residuals
1714  fill_in_contribution_to_residuals(residuals);
1715  //Allocate storage for the full residuals (residuals of entire element)
1716  unsigned n_dof = ndof();
1717  Vector<double> full_residuals(n_dof);
1718  //Get the residuals for the entire element
1719  get_residuals(full_residuals);
1720  //Calculate the contributions from the internal dofs
1721  //(finite-difference the lot by default)
1722  fill_in_jacobian_from_internal_by_fd(full_residuals,jacobian,true);
1723  //Calculate the contributions from the external dofs
1724  //(finite-difference the lot by default)
1725  fill_in_jacobian_from_external_by_fd(full_residuals,jacobian,true);
1726  //Calculate the contributions from the nodal dofs
1727  fill_in_jacobian_from_nodal_by_fd(full_residuals,jacobian);
1728  }

1731

1733  /// \short Function pointer for function that computes vector-valued
1734  /// steady "exact solution" \f$ {\bf f}({\bf x}) \f$
1735  /// as \f$ \mbox{\tt fct}({\bf x}, {\bf f}) \f$.
1736  typedef void (*SteadyExactSolutionFctPt)(const Vector<double>&,
1737  Vector<double>&);
1738 
1739  /// \short Function pointer for function that computes Vector-valued
1740  /// time-dependent function \f$ {\bf f}(t,{\bf x}) \f$
1741  /// as \f$ \mbox{\tt fct}(t, {\bf x}, {\bf f}) \f$.
1742  typedef void (*UnsteadyExactSolutionFctPt)(const double&,
1743  const Vector<double>&,
1744  Vector<double>&);

1746  /// \short Tolerance below which the jacobian is considered singular
1747  static double Tolerance_for_singular_jacobian;
1748 
1749  /// \short Boolean that if set to true allows a negative jacobian
1750  /// in the transform between global and local coordinates (negative surface
1751  /// area = left-handed coordinate system).
1752  static bool Accept_negative_jacobian;
1753 
1754  /// \short Static boolean to suppress output while checking
1755  /// for inverted elements
1756  static bool Suppress_output_while_checking_for_inverted_elements;

1758  /// Constructor

1852  /// \short Global coordinates as function of local coordinates.
1853  /// Either via FE representation or via macro-element (if Macro_elem_pt!=0)
1854  void get_x(const Vector<double> &s, Vector<double> &x) const
1855  {
1856  //If there is no macro element then return interpolated x
1857  if (Macro_elem_pt==0) {interpolated_x(s,x);}
1858  //Otherwise call the macro element representation
1859  else {get_x_from_macro_element(s,x);}
1860  }
1861 
1862 
1863  /// \short Global coordinates as function of local coordinates
1864  /// at previous time "level" t (t=0: present; t>0: previous).
1865  /// Either via FE representation of QElement or
1866  /// via macro-element (if Macro_elem_pt!=0).
1867  void get_x(const unsigned &t, const Vector<double> &s,
1868  Vector<double> &x)
1869  {
1870  // Get timestepper from first node
1871  TimeStepper* time_stepper_pt=node_pt(0)->time_stepper_pt();
1872 
1873  // Number of previous values
1874  const unsigned nprev=time_stepper_pt->nprev_values();
1875 
1876  // If t > nprev_values(), we're not dealing with a previous value
1877  // but a generalised history value -- this cannot be recovered from
1878  // macro element but must be determined by finite element interpolation
1879 
1880  //If there is no macro element, or we're dealing with a generalised
1881  //history value then use the FE representation
1882  if ((Macro_elem_pt==0)||(t>nprev)) {interpolated_x(t,s,x);}
1883  //Otherwise use the macro element representation
1884  else {get_x_from_macro_element(t,s,x);}
1885  }

1949  /// \short Function to compute the geometric shape functions and also
1950  /// first and second derivatives w.r.t.
1951  /// local coordinates at local coordinate s. This function must
1952  /// be overloaded for each specific geometric element (if required).
1953  /// (Broken virtual function --- specifies the interface).
1954  /// Numbering:
1955  /// \b 1D:
1956  /// d2psids(i,0) = \f$ d^2 \psi_j / ds^2 \f$
1957  /// \b 2D:
1958  /// d2psids(i,0) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial s_0^2 \f$
1959  /// d2psids(i,1) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial s_1^2 \f$
1960  /// d2psids(i,2) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial s_0 \partial s_1 \f$
1961  /// \b 3D:
1962  /// d2psids(i,0) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial s_0^2 \f$
1963  /// d2psids(i,1) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial s_1^2 \f$
1964  /// d2psids(i,2) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial s_2^2 \f$
1965  /// d2psids(i,3) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial s_0 \partial s_1 \f$
1966  /// d2psids(i,4) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial s_0 \partial s_2 \f$
1967  /// d2psids(i,5) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial s_1 \partial s_2 \f$
1968  virtual void d2shape_local(const Vector<double> &s,
1969  Shape &psi,
1970  DShape &dpsids,
1971  DShape &d2psids) const
1972  {
1973  throw OomphLibError(
1974  "d2shape_local() is not implemented for this element\n",
1975  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
1976  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
1977  }

1984  /// d2psids(i,0) = \f$ d^2 \psi_j / ds^2 \f$
1985  /// \b 2D:
1986  /// d2psids(i,0) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial s_0^2 \f$
1987  /// d2psids(i,1) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial s_1^2 \f$
1988  /// d2psids(i,2) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial s_0 \partial s_1 \f$

1990  /// d2psids(i,0) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial s_0^2 \f$
1991  /// d2psids(i,1) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial s_1^2 \f$

2297  /// \short This is an empty function that establishes a uniform
2298  /// interface for all (derived) elements that involve time-derivatives.
2299  /// Such elements are/should be implemented in ALE form to allow
2300  /// mesh motions. The additional expense associated with the
2301  /// computation of the mesh velocities is, of course, superfluous
2302  /// if the elements are used in problems in which the mesh is
2303  /// stationary. This function should therefore be overloaded
2304  /// in all derived elements that are formulated in ALE form
2305  /// to suppress the computation of the mesh velocities.
2306  /// The user disables the ALE functionality at his/her own risk!
2307  /// If the mesh does move after all, then the results will be wrong.
2308  /// Here we simply issue a warning message stating that the empty
2309  /// function has been called.
2310  virtual void disable_ALE()
2311  {
2312  std::ostringstream warn_message;
2313  warn_message
2314  << "Warning: You have just called the default (empty) function \n\n"
2315  << " FiniteElement::disable_ALE() \n\n"
2316  << "This suggests that you've either tried to call it for an element\n"
2317  << "that \n"
2318  << "(1) does not involve time-derivatives (e.g. a Poisson element) \n"
2319  << "(2) an element for which the time-derivatives aren't implemented \n"
2320  << " in ALE form \n"
2321  << "(3) an element for which the ALE form of the equations can't be \n"
2322  << " be disabled (yet).\n";
2323  OomphLibWarning(warn_message.str(),
2324  "Problem::disable_ALE()",
2325  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
2326  }
2327 
2328

2333  virtual void enable_ALE()

2339  << "This suggests that you've either tried to call it for an element\n"
2340  << "that \n"
2341  << "(1) does not involve time-derivatives (e.g. a Poisson element) \n"
2342  << "(2) an element for which the time-derivatives aren't implemented \n"
2343  << " in ALE form \n"
2344  << "(3) an element for which the ALE form of the equations can't be \n"
2345  << " be disabled (yet)\n"
2346  << "(4) an element for which this function has not been (properly) \n "

2572  /// \short Specify the values of the "global" intrinsic coordinate, zeta,
2573  /// of a compound geometric object (a mesh of elements) when
2574  /// the element is viewied as a sub-geometric object.
2575  /// The default assumption is that the element will be
2576  /// treated as a sub-geometric object in a bulk Mesh of other elements
2577  /// (geometric objects). The "global" coordinate of the compound geometric
2578  /// object is simply the Eulerian coordinate, x.
2579  /// The second default assumption is that the coordinate zeta will
2580  /// be stored at the nodes and interpolated using the shape functions
2581  /// of the element. This function returns the value of zeta stored at
2582  /// local node n, where k is the type of coordinate and i is the
2583  /// coordinate direction. The function is virtual so that it can
2584  /// be overloaded by different types of element: FaceElements
2585  /// and SolidFiniteElements
2586  virtual double zeta_nodal(const unsigned &n, const unsigned &k,
2587  const unsigned &i) const
2588  {
2589  //By default return the value for nodal_position_gen
2590  return nodal_position_gen(n,k,i);
2591  }

2594  /// \short Calculate the interpolated value of zeta, the intrinsic coordinate
2595  /// of the element when viewed as a compound geometric object within a Mesh
2596  /// as a function of the local coordinate of the element, s. The default
2597  /// assumption is the zeta is interpolated using the shape functions of
2598  /// the element with the values given by zeta_nodal().
2599  /// A MacroElement representation of the intrinsic coordinate parametrised
2600  /// by the local coordinate s is used if available.
2601  /// Choosing the MacroElement representation of zeta (Eulerian x by default)
2602  /// allows a correspondence to be established between elements on different
2603  /// Meshes covering the same curvilinear domain in cases where one element
2604  /// is much coarser than the other.

2750  /// \short Paraview output -- this outputs the coordinates at the plot
2751  /// points (for parameter nplot) to specified output file.
2752  void output_paraview(std::ofstream& file_out, const unsigned& nplot) const
2753  {
2754  //Decide the dimensions of the nodes
2755  unsigned nnod=nnode();
2756  if (nnod==0) return;
2757  unsigned n=node_pt(0)->ndim();
2758 
2759  // Vector for local coordinates
2760  Vector<double> s(n,0.0);
2761 
2762  //Vector for cartesian coordinates
2763  Vector<double> x(n,0.0);
2764 
2765  //Determine the total number of plotpoints
2766  unsigned plot=nplot_points_paraview(nplot);
2767 
2768  // Loop over the local points
2769  for (unsigned j=0; j<plot; j++)
2770  {
2771  // Determine where in the local element the point is
2772  this->get_s_plot(j,nplot,s);
2773 
2774  // Update the cartesian coordinates vector
2775  this->interpolated_x(s,x);
2776 
2777  // Print the global coordinates. Note: no whitespace after last
2778  // coordinate or paraview is very unhappy.
2779  for (unsigned i=0; i<n-1; i++)
2780  {
2781  file_out << x[i] << " ";
2782  }
2783  file_out << x[n-1];
2784 
2785  // Since unstructured grid always needs 3 components for each
2786  // point, output 0's by default
2787  switch (n)
2788  {
2789  case 1:
2790  file_out << " 0" << " 0"<< std::endl;
2791  break;
2792 
2793  case 2:
2794  file_out << " 0"<< std::endl;
2795  break;
2796 
2797  case 3:
2798  file_out << std::endl;
2799  break;
2800 
2801  // Paraview can't handle more than 3 dimensions, output error
2802  default:
2803  throw OomphLibError(
2804  "Printing PlotPoint to .vtu failed; it has >3 dimensions.",
2805  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
2806  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
2807  }
2808  }
2809  }

2811  /// \short Fill in the offset information for paraview plot. Broken virtual.
2812  /// Needs to be implemented for each new geometric element type; see

3357  class GeomObject;

3359  //=======================================================================
3360  /// \short A class to specify the initial conditions for a solid body.
3361  /// Solid bodies are often discretised with
3362  /// Hermite-type elements, for which the assignment
3363  /// of the generalised nodal values is nontrivial since they represent
3364  /// derivatives w.r.t. to the local coordinates. A SolidInitialCondition
3365  /// object specifies initial position (i.e. shape), velocity and acceleration
3366  /// of the structure with a geometric object.
3367  /// An integer specifies which time-derivative derivative is currently
3368  /// assigned. See example codes for a demonstration of its use.
3369  //=======================================================================
3370  class SolidInitialCondition
3371  {
3372 
3373  public:
3374 
3375  /// Constructor: Pass geometric object; initialise time deriv to 0
3376  SolidInitialCondition(GeomObject* geom_object_pt) :
3377  Geom_object_pt(geom_object_pt), IC_time_deriv(0)
3378  {};
3379 
3380 
3381  /// Broken copy constructor
3382  SolidInitialCondition(const SolidInitialCondition&)
3383  {
3384  BrokenCopy::broken_copy("SolidInitialCondition");
3385  }
3386 
3387  /// Broken assignment operator
3388  void operator=(const SolidInitialCondition&)
3389  {
3390  BrokenCopy::broken_assign("SolidInitialCondition");
3391  }
3392 
3393 
3394  /// (Reference to) pointer to geom object that specifies the initial condition
3395  GeomObject*& geom_object_pt()
3396  {
3397  return Geom_object_pt;
3398  }
3399 
3400  /// Which time derivative are we currently assigning?
3401  unsigned& ic_time_deriv()
3402  {
3403  return IC_time_deriv;
3404  }
3405 
3406 
3407  private:
3408 
3409  /// \short Pointer to the GeomObject that specifies the initial
3410  /// condition (shape, veloc and accel)
3411  GeomObject* Geom_object_pt;
3412 
3413  /// \short Which time derivative (0,1,2) are we currently assigning
3414  unsigned IC_time_deriv;
3415 
3416  };

3420  /////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////
3421  /////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////////

3423 
3424  //============================================================================
3425  /// \short SolidFiniteElement class.
3426  ///
3427  /// Solid elements are elements whose nodal positions are unknowns
3428  /// in the problem -- their nodes are SolidNodes. In such elements,
3429  /// the nodes not only have a variable (Eulerian) but also a fixed
3430  /// (Lagrangian) position. The positional variables have their own
3431  /// local equation numbering scheme which is set up with
3432  /// \code assign_solid_local_eqn_numbers () \endcode
3433  /// The derivatives of the
3434  /// `solid equations' (i.e. the equations that determine the
3435  /// nodal positions) with respect to the nodal positions, required
3436  /// in the Jacobian matrix, are determined by finite differencing.
3437  ///
3438  /// In the present form, the SolidFiniteElement represents
3439  /// a fully functional base class for `proper' solid mechanics elements,
3440  /// but it can also be combined
3441  /// (via inheritance) with elements that solve additional equations.
3442  /// This is particularly useful in cases where the solid equations
3443  /// are merely used to update the nodal positions in a moving mesh
3444  /// problem, although this can prove costly in practice.
3445  //============================================================================
3446  class SolidFiniteElement : public virtual FiniteElement
3447  {
3448 
3449  public:
3450 
3451  /// \short Set the lagrangian dimension of the element --- the number
3452  /// of lagrangian coordinates stored at the nodes in the element.
3453  void set_lagrangian_dimension(const unsigned &lagrangian_dimension)
3454  {Lagrangian_dimension = lagrangian_dimension;}
3455 
3456  /// \short Return whether there is internal solid data (e.g. discontinuous
3457  /// solid pressure). At present, this is used to report an error in
3458  /// setting initial conditions for ElasticProblems which can't
3459  /// handle such cases. The default is false.

3500  /// \short Specify Data that affects the geometry of the element
3501  /// by adding the position Data to the set that's passed in.
3502  /// (This functionality is required in FSI problems; set is used to
3503  /// avoid double counting).
3504  void identify_geometric_data(std::set<Data*> &geometric_data_pt)
3505  {
3506  //Loop over the node update data and add to the set
3507  const unsigned n_node=this->nnode();
3508  for (unsigned n=0; n<n_node; n++)
3509  {
3510  geometric_data_pt.insert(dynamic_cast<SolidNode*>(this->node_pt(n))
3511  ->variable_position_pt());
3512  }
3513  }

3516  /// \short In a SolidFiniteElement, the "global" intrinsic coordinate
3517  /// of the element when viewed as part of a compound geometric
3518  /// object (a Mesh) is, by default, the Lagrangian coordinate
3519  /// Note the assumption here is that we are always using isoparameteric
3520  /// elements in which the lagrangian coordinate is interpolated by the
3521  /// same shape functions as the eulerian coordinate.
3522  inline double zeta_nodal(const unsigned &n, const unsigned &k,
3523  const unsigned &i) const
3524  {return lagrangian_position_gen(n,k,i);}

3529  /// from the "current" MacroElement representation (if it exists -- if not,

3531  /// based representation to be used to apply displacement boundary

3596  /// \short Compute the geometric shape functions and also first
3597  /// and second derivatives w.r.t. Lagrangian coordinates at
3598  /// local coordinate s;
3599  /// Returns Jacobian of mapping from Lagrangian to local coordinates.
3600  /// Numbering:
3601  /// \b 1D:
3602  /// d2pidxi(i,0) = \f$ d^2 \psi_j / d \xi^2 \f$
3603  /// \b 2D:
3604  /// d2psidxi(i,0) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial \xi_0^2 \f$
3605  /// d2psidxi(i,1) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial \xi_1^2 \f$
3606  /// d2psidxi(i,2) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial \xi_0 \partial \xi_1 \f$
3607  /// \b 3D:
3608  /// d2psidxi(i,0) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial \xi_0^2 \f$
3609  /// d2psidxi(i,1) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial \xi_1^2 \f$
3610  /// d2psidxi(i,2) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial \xi_2^2 \f$
3611  /// d2psidxi(i,3) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j/\partial \xi_0 \partial \xi_1 \f$
3612  /// d2psidxi(i,4) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j/\partial \xi_0 \partial \xi_2 \f$
3613  /// d2psidxi(i,5) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j/\partial \xi_1 \partial \xi_2 \f$
3614  double d2shape_lagrangian(const Vector<double> &s, Shape &psi,
3615  DShape &dpsidxi, DShape &d2psidxi) const;
3616 
3617  /// \short Return the geometric shape functions and also first
3618  /// and second derivatives w.r.t. Lagrangian coordinates at
3619  /// the ipt-th integration point.
3620  /// Returns Jacobian of mapping from Lagrangian to local coordinates.
3621  /// Numbering:
3622  /// \b 1D:
3623  /// d2pidxi(i,0) = \f$ d^2 \psi_j / d^2 \xi^2 \f$
3624  /// \b 2D:
3625  /// d2psidxi(i,0) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j/\partial^2 \xi_0^2 \f$
3626  /// d2psidxi(i,1) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j/\partial^2 \xi_1^2 \f$
3627  /// d2psidxi(i,2) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j/\partial \xi_0 \partial \xi_1 \f$
3628  /// \b 3D:
3629  /// d2psidxi(i,0) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial^2 \xi_0^2 \f$
3630  /// d2psidxi(i,1) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial^2 \xi_1^2 \f$
3631  /// d2psidxi(i,2) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial^2 \xi_2^2 \f$
3632  /// d2psidxi(i,3) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j / \partial \xi_0 \partial \xi_1 \f$
3633  /// d2psidxi(i,4) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j/\partial \xi_0 \partial \xi_2 \f$
3634  /// d2psidxi(i,5) = \f$ \partial^2 \psi_j/\partial \xi_1 \partial \xi_2 \f$
3635  virtual double d2shape_lagrangian_at_knot(const unsigned &ipt,
3636  Shape &psi,
3637  DShape &dpsidxi,
3638  DShape &d2psidxi) const;

3654  /// Construct the local node n and return a pointer to it.
3655  Node* construct_node(const unsigned &n)
3656  {
3657  //Construct a solid node and assign it to the local node pointer vector.
3658  //The dimension and number of values are taken from internal element data
3659  //The number of solid pressure dofs are also taken from internal data
3660  //The number of timesteps to be stored comes from the problem!
3661  node_pt(n) = new SolidNode(lagrangian_dimension(),
3662  nnodal_lagrangian_type(),
3663  nodal_dimension(),
3664  nnodal_position_type(),
3665  required_nvalue(n));
3666  //Now return a pointer to the node, so that the mesh can find it
3667  return node_pt(n);
3668  }

3847  /// \short Compute the residuals for the setup of an initial condition.
3848  /// The global equations are:
3849  /// \f[
3850  /// 0 = \int \left( \sum_{j=1}^N \sum_{k=1}^K X_{ijk} \psi_{jk}(\xi_n)
3851  /// - \frac{\partial^D R^{(IC)}_i(\xi_n)}{\partial t^D}
3852  /// \right) \psi_{lm}(\xi_n) \ dv
3853  /// \mbox{ \ \ \ \ for \ \ \ $l=1,...,N, \ \ m=1,...,K$}
3854  /// \f]
3855  /// where \f$ N \f$ is the number of nodes in the mesh and \f$ K \f$
3856  /// the number of generalised nodal coordinates. The initial shape
3857  /// of the solid body, \f$ {\bf R}^{(IC)},\f$ and its time-derivatives
3858  /// are specified via the \c GeomObject that is stored in the
3859  /// \c SolidFiniteElement::SolidInitialCondition object. The latter also
3860  /// stores the order of the time-derivative \f$ D \f$ to be assigned.
3861  virtual void get_residuals_for_solid_ic(Vector<double>& residuals)
3862  {
3863  residuals.initialise(0.0);
3864  fill_in_residuals_for_solid_ic(residuals);
3865  }
3866 
3867  /// \short Fill in the residuals for the setup of an initial condition.
3868  /// The global equations are:
3869  /// \f[
3870  /// 0 = \int \left( \sum_{j=1}^N \sum_{k=1}^K X_{ijk} \psi_{jk}(\xi_n)
3871  /// - \frac{\partial^D R^{(IC)}_i(\xi_n)}{\partial t^D}
3872  /// \right) \psi_{lm}(\xi_n) \ dv
3873  /// \mbox{ \ \ \ \ for \ \ \ $l=1,...,N, \ \ m=1,...,K$}
3874  /// \f]
3875  /// where \f$ N \f$ is the number of nodes in the mesh and \f$ K \f$
3876  /// the number of generalised nodal coordinates. The initial shape
3877  /// of the solid body, \f$ {\bf R}^{(IC)},\f$ and its time-derivatives
3878  /// are specified via the \c GeomObject that is stored in the
3879  /// \c SolidFiniteElement::SolidInitialCondition object. The latter also
3880  /// stores the order of the time-derivative \f$ D \f$ to be assigned.
3881  void fill_in_residuals_for_solid_ic(Vector<double> &residuals)
3882  {
3883  //Call the generic residuals function with flag set to 0
3884  //using a dummy matrix argument
3885  fill_in_generic_jacobian_for_solid_ic(
3886  residuals,GeneralisedElement::Dummy_matrix,0);
3887  }
3888 
3889  /// \short Fill in the residuals and Jacobian for the setup of an
3890  /// initial condition. The global equations are:
3891  /// \f[
3892  /// 0 = \int \left( \sum_{j=1}^N \sum_{k=1}^K X_{ijk} \psi_{jk}(\xi_n)
3893  /// - \frac{\partial^D R^{(IC)}_i(\xi_n)}{\partial t^D}
3894  /// \right) \psi_{lm}(\xi_n) \ dv
3895  /// \mbox{ \ \ \ \ for \ \ \ $l=1,...,N, \ \ m=1,...,K$}
3896  /// \f]
3897  /// where \f$ N \f$ is the number of nodes in the mesh and \f$ K \f$
3898  /// the number of generalised nodal coordinates. The initial shape
3899  /// of the solid body, \f$ {\bf R}^{(IC)},\f$ and its time-derivatives
3900  /// are specified via the \c GeomObject that is stored in the
3901  /// \c SolidFiniteElement::SolidInitialCondition object. The latter also
3902  /// stores the order of the time-derivative \f$ D \f$ to be assigned.
3903  void fill_in_jacobian_for_solid_ic(Vector<double> &residuals,
3904  DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian)
3905  {
3906  //Call the generic routine with the flag set to 1
3907  fill_in_generic_jacobian_for_solid_ic(residuals,jacobian,1);
3908  }

3950  /// \short Calculate the mapping from local to lagrangian coordinates,
3951  /// given the derivatives of the shape functions w.r.t. local coorindates.
3952  /// Return the determinant of the jacobian, the jacobian and inverse jacobian
3953  virtual double local_to_lagrangian_mapping(
3954  const DShape &dpsids, DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian,
3955  DenseMatrix<double> &inverse_jacobian) const
3956  {
3957  //Assemble the jacobian
3958  assemble_local_to_lagrangian_jacobian(dpsids,jacobian);
3959  //Invert the jacobian
3960  return invert_jacobian_mapping(jacobian,inverse_jacobian);
3961  }
3962 
3963  /// \short Calculate the mapping from local to lagrangian coordinates,
3964  /// given the derivatives of the shape functions w.r.t. local coordinates,
3965  /// Return only the determinant of the jacobian and the inverse of the
3966  /// mapping (ds/dx)
3967  double local_to_lagrangian_mapping(const DShape &dpsids,
3968  DenseMatrix<double> &inverse_jacobian) const
3969  {
3970  //Find the dimension of the element
3971  unsigned el_dim = dim();
3972  //Assign memory for the jacobian
3973  DenseMatrix<double> jacobian(el_dim);
3974  //Calculate the jacobian and inverse
3975  return local_to_lagrangian_mapping(dpsids,jacobian,inverse_jacobian);
3976  }
3977 
3978  /// \short Calculate the mapping from local to Lagrangian coordinates given
3979  /// the derivatives of the shape functions w.r.t the local coorindates.
3980  /// assuming that the coordinates are aligned in the direction of the local
3981  /// coordinates, i.e. there are no cross terms and the jacobian is diagonal.
3982  /// This function returns the determinant of the jacobian, the jacobian
3983  /// and the inverse jacobian.
3984  virtual double local_to_lagrangian_mapping_diagonal(
3985  const DShape &dpsids,DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian,
3986  DenseMatrix<double> &inverse_jacobian) const;

4004  /// \short Access function that returns the local equation number that
4005  /// corresponds to the j-th coordinate of the k-th position-type at the
4006  /// n-th local node.
4007  inline int position_local_eqn(const unsigned &n, const unsigned &k,
4008  const unsigned &j) const
4009  {
4010 #ifdef RANGE_CHECKING
4011  std::ostringstream error_message;
4012  bool error=false;
4013  if (n >= nnode())
4014  {
4015  error = true;
4016  error_message << "Range Error: Nodal number " << n
4017  << " is not in the range (0,"
4018  << nnode() << ")";
4019  }
4020 
4021  if (k >= nnodal_position_type())
4022  {
4023  error = true;
4024  error_message << "Range Error: Position type " << k
4025  << " is not in the range (0,"
4026  << nnodal_position_type() << ")";
4027  }
4028 
4029  if (j >= nodal_dimension())
4030  {
4031  error=true;
4032  error_message << "Range Error: Nodal coordinate " << j
4033  << " is not in the range (0,"
4034  << nodal_dimension() << ")";
4035  }
4036 
4037  if (error)
4038  {
4039  //Throw the error
4040  throw OomphLibError(error_message.str(),
4041  OOMPH_CURRENT_FUNCTION,
4042  OOMPH_EXCEPTION_LOCATION);
4043  }
4044 #endif
4045 
4046  //Return the value
4047  return Position_local_eqn[(n*nnodal_position_type() + k)*nodal_dimension()
4048  + j];
4049  }

4054  /// \short Overload the fill_in_contribution_to_jacobian() function to
4055  /// use finite
4056  /// differences to calculate the solid residuals by default
4057  void fill_in_contribution_to_jacobian(Vector<double> &residuals,
4058  DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian)
4059  {
4060  //Add the contribution to the residuals
4061  fill_in_contribution_to_residuals(residuals);
4062 
4063  //Solve for the consistent acceleration in Newmark scheme?
4064  if (Solve_for_consistent_newmark_accel_flag)
4065  {
4066  fill_in_jacobian_for_newmark_accel(jacobian);
4067  return;
4068  }
4069 
4070  //Allocate storage for the full residuals (residuals of entire element)
4071  unsigned n_dof = ndof();
4072  Vector<double> full_residuals(n_dof);
4073  //Get the residuals for the entire element
4074  get_residuals(full_residuals);
4075  //Get the solid entries in the jacobian using finite differences
4076  fill_in_jacobian_from_solid_position_by_fd(full_residuals,jacobian);
4077  //There could be internal data
4078  //(finite-difference the lot by default)
4079  fill_in_jacobian_from_internal_by_fd(full_residuals,jacobian,true);
4080  //There could also be external data
4081  //(finite-difference the lot by default)
4082  fill_in_jacobian_from_external_by_fd(full_residuals,jacobian,true);
4083  //There could also be nodal data
4084  fill_in_jacobian_from_nodal_by_fd(full_residuals,jacobian);
4085  }

4089  /// \short Use finite differences to calculate the Jacobian entries
4090  /// corresponding to the solid positions. This version assumes
4091  /// that the residuals vector has already been computed

4093  fill_in_jacobian_from_solid_position_by_fd(Vector<double> &residuals,
4094  DenseMatrix<double> &jacobian);
